<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>GM Technology</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Victor M. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Shorrocks</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">M.A., D.Phil., </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">C.Biol</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">., M.S.B</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.1pt; padding-left:1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GM technology needs to be accepted by the public before it can be employed to further food security.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GM technology is precise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GM method</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> necessitates the use of an herbicide or antibiotic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">tolerant </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">gene. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GM technology can introduce genes not currently present in the DNA</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GM technology is no more unnatural than the technology,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">widely used since WW2 of creating mutants by radiation from which most of the crops we now grow are derived.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GM technology is another, not the only, tool for man to use in plant breeding and has a big potential for helping to achieve long term sustainable agriculture</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GM technology has the potential to help combat problems that are difficult to attack by other means.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GM technology can be kinder to the environment by reducing the use of insecticides and fungicides</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GM technology can help with achieving food security and sustainable agriculture because of its potential for benefits </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Motivation of the anti-GM camp seems less related to science and more to ideological positions maintained without supportive evidence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cultivation of GM crops in Europe should be facilitated partly because it will help African politicians remove barriers to the use of GM technology     </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.1pt; padding-left:1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Personal</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I am a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> retired agricultural scientist (b.1932) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">who worked on the mineral nutrition of crops specialising </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">latterly o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n micronutrients when I consulted worldwide.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">My reason for writing is because I feel that the issue of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the use of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">GM </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">technology still </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">suffers from too much ignorance about </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">its </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nature and how it compares with existing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">methods of plant breeding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> let alone what problems it may help to solve.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The story of what GM technology amounts to needs to be more widely understood before it will be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">accepted especially in Europe. Acceptance is a prerequisite for the use of GM technology in north-west Europe and Africa.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.1pt; padding-left:1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Essential features of GM technology</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Herbicide tolerance is an integral aspect</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">GM technology relies on the transfer of identified genes into the existing DNA of cells. The identified gene may be taken from another organism or they can be constructed in the laboratory. The transfer is achieved either using a bacteria (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Agrobacterium</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) to do the job or by shooting the gene attached to microscopic gold particles into a soup of cells.  This is a hit and miss affair</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">few cells</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (as few as 1 in 1,000) that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">receive the gene</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> need to be separated from the rest order to avoid the impossibly massive amount of cell culture work to grow whole plants from each cell</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Luckily a gene that conferred </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">toler</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ance to the herbicide</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">glyphosate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Monsanto) and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">glufosinate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Bayer) were known</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. So </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t became routine for th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ese</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> gene</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to be inserted at the same time as the desired gene. The addition of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a herbicide </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to the soup of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">treated </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cells killed off the cells that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> had not got the desired gene (the antibiotic sulfonylurea was used by BASF in analogous way</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">). So began the dominance of Monsanto with their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">glyphosate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tolerant</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> soya, maize</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, oilseed rape, sugar beet</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and cotton. Patents </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are now expiring on some of the varieties</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">so</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> farmers will be able to keep seed free of charge. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Bayer developed varieties of oilseed rape, rice, soya and sugar beet tolerant to the herbicide </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">glufosinate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.1pt; padding-left:1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Precision of</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GM technology</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">G</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ene transfer is attractive to plant breeders as it allows identified beneficial genes to be added to existing good varieties relatively easily. This is to be contrasted</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">imprecise </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ways </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">new improved varieties have been bred in the past</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> GM technology is a precise way of introducing a gene for a specific effect which causes minimal changes to the original DNA.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is theoretically possible that the introduction </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of one or two genes </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">might alter the performance of existing genes that might turn out to be deleterious.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> This aspect is addressed in the safety evaluation of GM crops.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.1pt; padding-left:1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Crop improvement by selection and crossing</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Crops </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have historically been </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">improved initially by s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">electin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> seed from better grown plants in the field for use next year</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The next step was the artificial crossing by the transfer of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">pollen from and to plants with desirable characteristics followed by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">laborious long term </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">studies </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(10-15 years) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to select beneficial progeny</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from the random crosses. Even this innocent procedure of the mixing of two sets of DNA could have unexpected and undesirable consequences.</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.1pt; padding-left:1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Genes need to be present to be selected</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If a gene for a desirable trait e.g. resistance to a particular disease </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s not present originally then no amount of selection </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">or crossing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">will find it.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.1pt; padding-left:1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Mutagenesis</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The ability to cause mutations (mutagenesis) by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">subjecting</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">plant material</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> especially seed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s to ionising </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">radiati</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n or</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">less</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> commonly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> chemical</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">has been used ex</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ensively since WW</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as a means of creating </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mutants with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">new genes. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">chaotic random </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">procedure hopefully results in plants with desirable characteristics that can then be crossed with existing valuable varieties. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Over 3,200 varieties of more than 200 species have been developed by the unregulated</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> use of such mutants </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and are in use in about 100 countries</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Most of our crops have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">man-made </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mutants in their ancestry</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">One such crop is</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a mutant variety of barley produced by subjecting the seed to gamma rays now used to make the organic beer, Golden Promise. Does the organic movement in the UK notably the Soil Association and its patron Prince Charles consider </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">radiation </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mutagenesis to be a natural procedure? </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> A central plank of their </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">objecti</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to GM </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is that we</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mov</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">into the unnatural </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“realms that belong to God and to God alone”.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.1pt; padding-left:1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">No</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> regulation or testing of mutants</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> or mutant-derived varieties</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is notable that despite the use of radiation there has been no regulation or testing of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mutant-derived </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">varieties for safety for man</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> animals and the environment, a situation which is to be contrasted with the detailed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">safety testing and evaluation of GM varieties</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> .</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is likely that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mutagenesis </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">will cause </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">more changes to the DNA than </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">those </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">evident </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">improvement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">uch changes could well </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lead to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> proteins that are allergens or toxins</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of which we are ignorant.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> In contrast the possibility of allergen and toxin production by GM varieties is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">evaluated making them potentially safer than mutant-derived varieties.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Mutagenesis is seeing a resurgence in view of the absence of regulation. </span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.1pt; padding-left:1pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">GM potential </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Second and Third generation GM crops</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Crops with insect resistant properties</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The first GM crops that were commercialised were crops such as soya and maize that were</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> tolerant of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a single herbicide</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the consequence of the GM methodology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Insect resistance was transferred into </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">maize, cotton and potatoes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">bacterium</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Bacillus </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">thuringiensis</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> which produces an insecticidal protein in the crops themselves (now called Bt crops). The o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rganic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">objectors to GM p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ermit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> their farmers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to use </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">insecticidal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">spray</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s and dusts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> derived from </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Bacillus </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">thuringiensis</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">but not the Bt crops which is illogical. The gene for making t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ecticidal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">protein</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">could not be introduced by conventional breeding.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Crops with improved nutrition</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Work aimed at p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reventin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> vitamin A deficiency by improving the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">dietary </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">intake of the precursor β carotene </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">exemplifies </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the different approaches that can be employed.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Rice, a staple for millions in South East Asia does not contain β carotene. If rice </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s to be used as a vehicle for β carotene then it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> necessary to introduce the gene for its production</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; this was</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> done initially with a gene from the daffodil and then </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a more efficient gene from maize to create Golden Rice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Syngenta</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The improved rice varieties have been crossed with established local varieties.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In contrast sweet potato (widely consumed in Africa but not South East Asia) does contain β carotene and so can be improved by conventional breeding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> without gene transfer.</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Improved photosynthesis, N fixation by cereals </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">All concerned with he</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lping</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> man to feed the anticipated global 10 billion have to consider </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">all possibilities to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">improve crops. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is reassuring to know that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">research programmes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">aimed at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">improving photosynthesis and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> conferring the ability </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for cereals </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to fix atmospheric nitrogen are under way in the UK. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The potential benefits are so immense that success would probably lead to another “Green Revolution”. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is an inevitable consequence of all agricultural systems that nutrients are removed from the soil an effect that can be partly mitigated by recycling. In time the soil is unable to supply sufficient available minerals which need replenishing by application of appropriate fertilisers. Apart from nitrogenous fertilisers, which can be manufactured without the use of a finite raw material (at present they rely on oil), the current raw materials for fertilisers will eventually run out</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It will be necessary to use new, currently unusable, raw materials. The roots of some crops are known to exude chemicals that have the power to solubilise unavailable iron and manganese which plants can then absorb. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s not difficult to imagine extend</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> this work to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">all essential plant nutrients</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Every effort should be made in Westminster and in the EU to facilitate the cultivation of GM crops in the UK and in Europe.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Whilst it may take some time for public perception in the UK to warm to GM crops the very fact of a change will alter perceptions in many African countries where politicians are blocking GM developments because they are taking a lead from the EU. Improvements in the disease resistance of such crops as cassava and banana could make a big difference for many in Africa and be an ample reward for changes in Europe. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Review of the arguments of opponents of GM technology</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The arguments made by the opponents fall into two categories. Firstly arguments that are relevant to the technology itself and those that are related to the use of GM crops in the field which are basically irrelevant.</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Arguments relevant to GM technology</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Not Natural</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Possibly the most commonly used argument is that the procedure is not natural and results in “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">frankenfoods</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">”. If natural is meant to be what nature could manage without man’s help then GM technology is not natural. But so is mutagenesis which we do not object to. </span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Not Safe</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The claim that GM food is not safe for man, animals and the environment is repeatedly made and leads to demands for long term toxicology studies to demonstrate the absolute safety of GM derived food. There can never be absolute proof that there will never be any deleterious effects of GM crops. Such absolute proof cannot be demonstrated for any human activity.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The safety of all the GM crops currently grown across the world has been assessed by local regulatory bodies. The key aspect of all assessments is to determine whether the GM crop is fundamentally the same as its non-GM counterpart. </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">WHO, </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the American Medical Association, the US National Academy of Sciences, the UK Royal Society and </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">other respected scientific organisations have </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">concluded that </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">GM crop</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s pose no greater risk than crop plants modified conventional</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ly.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Escape of genes into other plants </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Genes can of course escape by pollen transfer and may successfully enter the DNA of other plants - an aspect that is monitored. The beneficial attributes transferred to another plant might help its survival. For over 50 years it has been possible for the benefits conferred by mutagenesis assisted plant breeding to be transferred to other plants without any untoward happening. It may also be pointed out that for a few hundred years we have imported plants (over 2000 species) with their foreign genes into the UK again without deleterious effects of gene transfer.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Organic groups look upon gene transfer from a GM crop to an organic crop as contamination in order to provide a rationale for their self-ordained regulations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Arguments irrelevant to GM technology</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Super weeds, Insecticide and fungicide resistant pests.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> first attribute of GM crops was tolerance to the herbicide </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">glyphosate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> which meant that this herbicide could be sprayed to kill competing weeds without damaging the crop. Long before GM technology appeared it was known that repeated use of the same herbicide was likely to lead to the weed cultivars tolerant of the herbicide surviving and propagating next year. In the same way insects that are not killed by the insect resistant GM crop will survive and multiply. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The involvement of GM technology is incidental. The problems of super weeds etc. will be solved,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">whether the crop is GM or not, by the use of other herbicide and pesticides and by improvements to agricultural practices.</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">La</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rge Agribusinesses will control farmer across the world</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Because Monsanto were in the vanguard with their herbicide </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">glyphosate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> they attracted the attention of the GM opponents. They are no longer alone </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Syngenta</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (who have donated their Golden Rice work to third world farmers) and others including Bayer, BASF, Dow, Du Pont Pioneer have joined them.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">GM opponents ignore the basic fact that farmers are not coerced into buying anyone’s seed; they will only buy a particular variety if they perceive it to be a benefit to them. Hybrid seed has to be bought annually from the producer. The perceived unacceptable commercial practices of Monsanto are not valid reasons for rejecting GM technology. </span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">There are other ways of achieving the same end result</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is often more than one way of solving a problem but it is not logical to disregard an approach on this basis. The ways that prove easier to use, are more beneficial or are cheaper are likely to prevail. Marker assisted plant breeding is a very valuable tool and where applicable will be used. The proposed use of Golden Rice to combat the deadly vitamin A deficiency by improving the diet is simpler and cheaper than the alternative solution of providing 6 monthly vitamin A supplements to all children less than 5 years.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Precautionary principle</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is easy to claim that as everything or not enough is not known about the outcome of a new process the precautionary principle should be adopted. Discussion of the principle is more likely to be at a theoretical level rather than evidence based at the scientific level. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Is the precautionary principle adopted as a delaying tactic by people who ostensibly appear to be protecting the population from fears that they have created?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Why do people oppose GM</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Influence of</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> media following </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">stories of </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">frankenfood</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and crop trashing</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Amongst the first people to oppose GM technology in the UK were Prince Charles, the Soil Association and Greenpeace. The former’s opposition was based on the unnatural aspect and the “playing God” with nature. The opposition  of the Soil Association was said to be based on a study of the evidence which considering this was in the late 1990s before little was in the public domain about GM is difficult to accept: the ill-advised and flawed claims of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Pusztai</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> had not been made to the media (1998).  The Soil Association backed and participated with Greenpeace, in the destruction of open field experiments with GM crops in 1998 and 1999 activities which attracted a lot of media attention. The rallying call from the Soil Association was that GM crops would contaminate organic crops with what result was not specified; Prince Charles (patron of the Soil Association) supported this hype. Before the Soil Association took an anti-GM position the sales of organic food in the UK (70% imported) were about £200 million; in 1998 and 1999 organic sales increased in both years by over 50%.  Did the massive media publicity given to the trashing of GM crop trials and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">frankenfoods</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> helped sales of organic food? The Soil Association, a commercial organisation, depends on negatives (e.g. no man-made fertilisers or pesticides are allowed) in its promotion. Was anti-GM just another convenient negative to promote sales?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The largely uncritical media fed the public a diet of “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">frankenfoods</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">” and trial trashing that was countered by only minimal opposition from the scientific fraternity. This led to many people to conforming to what they thought was the common perception and accepting the premise that GM technology was to be avoided.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Positions that lacked a basis other than ideological</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or commercial</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> were taken up in the early days of the GM story. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">For example </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Greenpeace, Friends of the Earth and the Soil Association were </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">unable, at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an OECD </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Biosafety</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Conference in Edinburgh in 2000</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, to provide evidence to support their claims that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">GM foods </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">could damage </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">human health</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Parallel with organic food</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A parallel can sadly be drawn with the claims that organic food is healthier than traditionally grown food. The scientific community has known there is no basis for this claim. The truth was give media prominence in 2009 by the Food Standard Agency but  surveys still show that people buy organic food because they believe it is healthier and contains less pesticides (which is also not true).  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is likely that the public will respond similarly to GM technology and will never fully accept it despite the evidence in its favour. Politicians will have to take the lead and Owen Patterson is to be complimented in this regard.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Sustainable agriculture and food security</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">GM technology can help to achieve sustainable agriculture due to its ability to improve crop performance in precise ways for local crop/climate conditions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is said that current food production is sufficient if we were not wasteful. Likewise the proponents or organic agriculture maintain that the world can feed itself by farming organically. This they say requires the human race to renounce the consumption of animal products and so reduce the need for cereals. The ideas that the human race, especially as it becomes wealthier will become vegetarian and waste less is an unlikely proposition.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Atmospheric nitrogen is converted into organic nitrogenous compounds by bacteria living in symbiotic relationship with plants (e.g. the pea and bean family) and by free-living bacteria in the soil.  The current total global biological fixation of nitrogen is sufficient to provide enough protein for about 3 billion people. The rest mostly comes from man-made nitrogen fixation in factories. Without fundamental changes that one day may be achieved by transferring the nitrogen fixing ability to other plants by GM technology this truth will remain. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There will be a need to increase, possibly double, the production of man-made nitrogenous fertilisers in order to feed the anticipated stabilised global population of 10 billion.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>